{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2abbott_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280604689/1946020901/0165.xml":{"full_text":"'On the Other Hand\u2019\n\u2018Don\u2019t Sell America Short\u2019 Slogan\nStill Being Ignored by Many Bigots\nBy Lowell Mellett\n\u201cDon\u2019t sell America short.\"\nPerhaps you remember how that\nslogan originated. One friend when\nasked was disposed to attribute\nIts authorship to\nAndrew W. Mel\nlon and to link\nit with another\n\u2014\u201cProsperity is\nJust around the\ncorner.\u201d Whether\nor not the then\nCoorotn y'Xr nf tVin\nTreasury coined\nIt or ever used it,\nthe slogan was\ngiven a great\nworkout in that\nperilous period\nwhen there were\ntwo empty pots\nfor ever>chicken Loweii Meiiett.\nand prosperity remained around the\ncorner.\nAnother friend is positive that\nthe slogan goes all the way back to\nJ. P. Morgan, the elder. As he re\nmembers it, the occasion was the\nformation of our first billion-dollar\ncorporation, an enterprise promoted\nby the House of Morgan. There\nwere those who thought the vast\namount pi water incorporated into\nthe new steel trust might be bad\nfor the national economy. And it\nwas to answer such doubtful per\nsons that Mr. Morgan admonished\nthem not to sell America short, ac\ncording to this friend\u2014who admits,\nhowever, that his memory may be\nless than perfect.\nSlogan Called Good.\nWhoever the author may be and\nwhatever misuse may be made of\nthe slogan, it is a good one, since it\nsimply translates into stock mar\nket lingo a clearer and better one\u2014\n\u2018\u2018Have faith in America.\u201d\nA reminder of the need for such\nfaith was given the other night by\nAssociate Justice Black of the Su\npreme Court. \u201cI have no fear of\nRussia,\u201d he said. \"It shocks me to\nhear some of the statements made\nin this country today. I think I\nknow why they are made. I think\nit's because the people who make\nthem disapprove of Russia\u2019s eco\nnomic system and fear it. As I\nunderstand America, we have no\nreason to fear the ideas of any coun\ntrv nn parth\nIt is too bad that the little band\nof bigots that compose the active\nmajority of the House Un-American\nCommittee do not have this same\nunderstanding of America and the\nsame faith in our country. They ap\npear to fear the ideas of every coun\ntry on earth, with the possible ex\nception of Nazi Germany. For ex\nample, nearly every country has the\nidea that this country of ours is a\ndemocracy. (And so, you say, it is.)\nBut the Un-American Committee,\nthrough its chief counsel, writes to\na veterans\u2019 organization and says:\n\u201cSeveral of your circulars\u201d have\nbeen sent to us by citizens of your\ncity and I note that you refer to\ndemocracy Vseveral times. I wonder\nIf you are sufficiently familiar with\nthe history of the United States to\nbe aware that this country was not\norganized as a democracy\nLack of Faith Cited.\nAnd he demands of the veterans\nthat they tell him if it is their pur\npose to ask for amendment of the\nConstitution! Obviously he and his\ncommittee lack faith, not only in\ndemocracy, but in America's ability\nto resist any argument in favor of\ndemocracy\u2014assuming we really are\nnot a democracy.\nThere are others who lack faith,\nwho persist in selling America short.\nThey line up to preach against and\nto vote against the proposal to make\nfull employment one of the real re\nsponsibilities of our Government.\nThis cannot, in their opinion, be\ncome a country in which every\ncitizen, able to work and desiring to\nwork, will have a job at decent\nwages. They have not that much\nfaith in America.\nThey oppose the idea of a 65\ncent minimum wage. They haven\u2019t\nthat much faith in the rich re\nsources of our country.\nAnd then there are those who\nrefuse to contemplate the necessity\nof paying living wages to the men\nand wofnen who made the goods\nthat wen the war and similar wages\nto the men who fought the war\nmd are now coming home to resume\nlife in the country for which they\nfought. Despite accumulated re\nserves of war profits they want\nA ZI I\ntheir peacetime profit* assured In\nadvance\u2014just as their war profits\nwere\u2014before they will agree to take\na chance on America. This at a\ntime when our business outlook is\nabout the best we\u2019ve ever known.\nThese latter, if they only knew\nit, are guilty of something even\n,worse than selling. America short.\nThey are actually selling their own\nreligion, free enterprise, short.\nAnswers to\nQuestions\nA reader can get the answer to any\nQuestion of fact by writing The Evening\nStsr Information Bureau. 31fl I street\nWashington 2. D. C. Please In*\nclose 3 cents for return oostage.\nBy THE HASKIN SERVICE.\nQ. Are horseshoes made of iron\nAnswers to\nQuestions\nA reader can get the answer to any\nQuestion of fact by writing The Evening\n\u00a3t*r Information Bureau. 310 I street\nN.E.. Washington 2. D. C. Please in'\nclose 3 cents for return nostage.\nBy THE HASKIN SERVICE.\nQ. Are horseshoes made of iron\nvi otcrri f\u2014j_i. XJ. a.\nA. According to the American\nIron and Steel Institute, practically\nall horseshoes are made of steel.\nThe exceptions are some racing\nshoes of aluminum. To produce 20,\n000,000 shoes needed each year,\nabout 20,000 tons of steel are re\nquired.\nQ. How long does frozen milk\nkeep its flavor?\u2014R. E. S.\nA. The milk holds its fresh flavor\nwell for as long as three or four\nmonths. Frozen milk as used on\nhospital ships by the Army is\npasteurized, homogenized and kept\nfrozen in paper containers until\nthawed for serving.\nQ. Why was \u201cOperation Pluto\u201d\ncalled by this particular name?\u2014\nS. B. S.\nA. This name was derived from\nthe initial letters of the title, \u201cPipe\nLines Under the Ocean.\u201d These\npipe lines, secretly laid across the\nEnglish Channel, were an import\ntant factor in the successful Invasion\naf France in 1944.\nQ. Please explain the significance\nof Ember Days?\u2014K. R. B.\nA. Ember Days are days set apart\nror fasting and prayer in each of\nthe four seasons. They were known\nto have been observed in Britain\nis early as 597 and were affirmed\nby the Council of Aenham. 1009,\nand appointed by the Council of\nPlacentia, 1095.\nQ. Is the tobacco plant useful in\nany other way than to produce\ncigars and cigarettes?\u2014R. w.\nA. Among by-products of tobacco\nare tobacco dusts, insecticides and\nfertilizer. Lately a crop has been\n?rown for the extraction of nicotinic\nacid, an important drug in the\ntreatment of pellagra.\nQ. How many Baptist bodies are\nthere in the United States?\u2014\nK. L. W.\nA. There are in the United States\n22 bodies of Baptists, each of which\nhas its own particular doctrine.\nQ. Is the State of New Jersey\npaying a bonus to veterans of World\nWar II?\u2014V. E. D.\nA. Yes. New Jeresy is one of the\nfew States which now pay such\na bonus.\nQ. How many bands were there\nn the Army and Navy during the\nwar?\u2014R. s. L.\nA. No exact figure is available.\nPractically every unit, large or small,\nnad a band and the majority were\nBfficial. During the time of peak\nstrength there would have been\nhundreds of bands in any one of the\nBranches of the service. The max\nimum number of bands serving in\nthe Coast Guard at any one time\nduring World War II was 32. This\nincluded 20 serving in the United\nStates, 3 at overseas shore establish\nments and 9 aboard Ooast Guard\nmanned transports.\nBrakes Relined\nPLYMOUTH $Qi60\nCHEVROLET w\nCLIFT'S SSL\n2002 K St. N.W._ ME. 6332\nr \u25a0\u2014i\nEisenhower fo Address\nNational Service Class\nArmy Chief of Staff Eisenhower\nwill be principal speaker at gradua\ntion ceremonies at 4 p.m. tomorrow\nfor 35 national service officer trainees\nof the Disabled American Veterans\nat American University.\nAlso planning to attend the cere\nmctoy, which will be held at the\nMetropolitan Memorial Church, is\nGen. Omar N. Bradley, veterans\u2019 ad\nministrator. Gen. Eisenhower said\nyesterday he will give a \u201csoldier-to\nsoldier, heart-to-heart,\u201d unprepared\ntalk.\nJohn O. Goelz of Cincinanti will\ngive the valedictory address to the\nformer GIs, completing a six-week\ncourse for national service officer po\nsitions.\nThe graduates, all World War II\ndisabled men, will leave Monday for\nCincinnati, where they will receive\nfinal instructions from DAV national\nheadquarters before being assigned\nto service offices throughout the\ncountry.\nRev. Frank Dorey Guest\nAt Luther Memorial\nThe Rev. Frank Dorey, of Howard\nUniversity, former acting pastor of\n\u201cThe Church of the Crossroads\u2019\u2019\nHonolulu, T. H., will speak at the\nLuther Place Memorial Church on\n\u201cReligious and Racial Tension To\nday\u201d before the Young People's\nLuther League at 6:30 p.m. tomor\nrow.\nThe senior Luther League will\nhave a round-table discussion at\n6:30 p.m. on \"Are Boys a Problem,\nToo?\u201d Only the girls will take part.\nAll teen-agers are invitied.\nThere will be a missionary rally\nat 3 p.m. for all intermediates of\nthe Washington District Luther\nLeague, at St. Luke\u2019s Lutheran\nChurch, Silver Spring, Mji.\nNational Baptist Church\nDr. Edward B. Willingham, pastor\nof National Baptist Memorial\nChurch, will use for his subject at\n11 a.m. tomorrow, \u201cOur Sacrifice for\nHim,\" continuing the theme, \"His\nSacrifice for Us.\u201d As a part of the\nWorld Mission Crusade in which the\nchurch is now engaged, a sacrificial\noffering will be made for world re\nlief and the rehabilitation of mis\nsion stations. At 8 p.m. he will bring\nthe second in the series of sermons\non \u201cChristian Values in Love, Court\nship and Marriage,\u201d entitled, \u201cI,\nJohn, Take Thee, Mary.\u201d\nTh$ Sunday School Board will\nmeet for dinner at 6 pun. Wednes\nday, followed by the all-circle meet\ning of the Woman\u2019s Society.\nWar Hospitality Group\nTo Mark Anniversary\nThe War Hospitality Committe\u2019s\ninformation service handled 507,411\ninquiries during 1945, according to\na report prepared in connection\nwith the service\u2019s fourth anniver\nsary, which will be celebrated at\n4:30 p.m. today in the home of\nMme. Laura Barney, 2306 Massa\nchusetts avenue N.W.\nApproximately half of the 1,051\nvolunteers trained in the four-year\nperiod still are active at informa\ntion desks, the report stated.\nMrs. Clifford Davis, wife of the\nRepresentaive from Tennessee, is\nchairman of the service.\nnz.__-_rrzn\n2,000th Broadcast\nMarked by Crowley\nEvangelist Dale Crowley, radio\nminister, has attained his two thou\nsandth radio program over local\nstations. He conducts the \u2018\u2018Right\nStart for the Day\u201d program over\nstation WWDC daily, at 6:45 a.m.,\nand the Bible Quiz on Saturdays\nat 7 p.m. over the same station.\nFeatured on the Bible Quiz to\nnight will be the Navigators, an in\nternational orgnization of Bible\nstudlng seamen.\nDr. Bentley to Preach\nAt Foundry Methodist\nDr. John E. Bentley of American\nUniversity, will be the guest preacher\nat 8 p.m. tomorrow at Foundry\nMethodist Church. His subject is\n\u201cItaly at Prayer.\"\nAt the meeting of the Foundry\nForge at 7 p.m., Lt. (J. g.) Harry\nBurkholder, Gwendolyn Fillman,\nVirginia Stone, Capt. Gene Frye and\nJames Crenshaw will form a panel\nfor the discussion of \"Labor and\nManagement.\"\nMrs. Leslie Clark Stevens, world\nDOUBLE SERVICES EVERY\nSUNDAY MORNING\n9:00 and 11:00 A M.\nIn an effort to accommodate aU her\nfrlendi and vtaltora the New York\nAvenue Preabyterlan Church haa Inatl\ntuted a 9 o'clock aervlce. The aervlcei\nwill be. ai nearly ai ponible. Identical.\nAll ceati will be available at the early\naervlce. No one will be aeated for tho\nsecond aervlce until 10:35.\nThe Sunday School wi|l continue to meet\nat 0:30 A.M. with claaaea for all area.\nNEW YORK AVENUE\nPRESBYTERIAN CHURCH\nNew York Avt. ot 13th and H Stt. N.W.\ntraveler and lecturer, will be ten\ndered a luncheon by the Woman's\nSociety of Christian Service at the\nLetts House Tuesday. She will\nspeak on \"Children of Russia.\"\nAlbright Memorial\nAt 11 a.m. tomorrow, at Albright\nMemorial Church, the Rev. George\nE. Schnabel will preach a second\nin the series of sermons on \"Victim\nor Victor.\u201d\nAs a part of the race relations!\nprogram, the young people of the\nJohn Wesley A. M. E. Zion Church\nwill be guests at 7 p.m. and at 8\no\u2019clock the Young Adult Fellowship\nwill participate in the services.\nDr. Mattice to Speak\nDr. Gordon Mattice, pastor of\nWestminster Presbyterian Church,\nRochester, N. Y., will be the speaker\nat the Thursday dinner conference\nat the Chevy Chase Presbyterian\nChurch. His subject will be \u2018\u2018The\nSpiritual Use of Economic Oppor\ntunity.\"\nThe Rev. Donald L. Leonard, as\n(Eliriatian lUfurmeb\nMmmmmmmmmmmmmmmm\u2014mam\u2014mmmmmmmmammmi\nsistant minister, will occupy tha\npulpit at 11 am. Sunday. His\nsubject will be \u2018\u2018Thou Shalt Talk of\nThem.\u201d\nBrrtijrftt\n\u25a0M\u2014h\u2014mSBmmmmm, I \u2014B\nWashington Brethren\n619 D Street 8.E.\nCLARENCE FAIRBANKS. Minister\n10.00 am.\u2014Sunder School.\n11:00 e.m.\u2014\"Conviction of Conduct.**\n7:00 p.m.\u2014\"A Sincere Faith.\u2019\u2019\nWednesday. 2:00 p.m.\u2014W. M. S.\nDay of Prayer.\nrnrrrfi\nQHjrifltian lUfnrmeb\nthe most Important\nPyblication of 1946\ni\nThe Revised\nStandard\nVersion of the j\nNew\nTestament\nAn authorized revision of\nthe American Standard\nVersion of 1901 and the\nKing James Version of\n1611.\nCritics agree a version\nmore accurate in transla\ntion than any previous,\nand, because of its beauti\nful modern English, more\nuseful, understandable, and\npleasurable to the 20th\nCentury reader.\nPrice $2.00\niljlBLES\nIn All Versions\nTestaments and Prayer Books\nPulpit Bibles for Memorials\nHallmark A Norcroaa Greetinc Cardi\nPursell's Book Store\n807 G Sf. N.W.\nDIat. 164* Eat. 1865\n\u2014\u2014I\u2014r\nBrakes Relined\nFORD\nPLYMOUTH\nCHEVROLET\nFree Adjustments.\nDuplicate D. C. Te